b'While I don\xe2\x80\x99t doubt that personalized medicine is the future and cancer genomics will be big. I doubt that $PACB will play as big a part in it, largely because it is a relatively old technology which has been adapted to compete better against $ILMN and customers don\xe2\x80\x99t appear 8/n'

b'That long suffering shareholders finally got a reprieve (me included :))when $ILMN offered to buy them for $8. But that was ruled out to prevent a monopoly, bringing the stock back to the 4s until ...6/n'

b'So why doesn\xe2\x80\x99t everyone just use $PACB. The biggest issue is speed, throughput or the amount of DNA data is a lot lower than $ILMN. The machine is also way more expensive and raw accuracy is lower while this can be improved through triangulation to a very high degree 4/n'

b'and puts it back together. $PACB splits into pieces as long as 50k(?). The assembly is a software problem, but the bigger the constituent pieces the better assembly can be. 10X Genomics $TXG labels $ILMN to be able to come up with longer pieces. 3/n'

b'$PACB is a next-gen sequencer, ie they make machines similar to $ILMN. The big difference being that they provide long reads. Human DNA is about 3 billion bases (ATCG). In order to read every base to find out which it is, $ILMN splits into pieces of a few hundred 2/n'

b'@leonardmazza @stevenmarkryan $PACB because long read sequencing has potential to displace some of the short read market share dominated by $ILMN.\n\n$NVTA have the most data and potential network effects compared to its competitors.'
